# Backend: GraphQL

## Schema Design
- Use descriptive type and field names; follow domain language
- Define input types for mutations; never accept raw JSON
- Use enums for fixed sets of values
- Add descriptions to all types, fields, and arguments in the schema
- Version via schema evolution (additive changes), not URL versioning

## Resolver Patterns
- Keep resolvers thin — delegate business logic to services
- Use DataLoader to prevent N+1 queries in nested resolvers
- Return typed errors via a union type or `errors` field; never throw untyped exceptions
- Validate input at the resolver boundary using Zod, Joi, or equivalent

## Pagination
- Use Relay-style cursor-based pagination (`first`, `after`, `last`, `before`)
- Return `edges` and `pageInfo` with `hasNextPage` and `endCursor`
- Never use offset-based pagination for large datasets

## Security
- Enforce authentication in middleware or directives, not in individual resolvers
- Implement query depth limiting (max depth 7–10)
- Implement query complexity analysis to prevent expensive queries
- Disable introspection in production
- Rate-limit by query complexity, not just request count

## Performance
- Use persisted queries or automatic persisted queries (APQ) in production
- Enable response caching with appropriate cache-control hints
- Use `@defer` and `@stream` directives for large responses when supported
- Monitor resolver execution time; alert on p99 > 500ms

## Conventions
- Co-locate schema and resolvers by domain (e.g. `orders/schema.graphql`, `orders/resolvers.ts`)
- Generate types from schema using codegen (e.g. GraphQL Code Generator)
- Write integration tests against the actual GraphQL endpoint, not individual resolvers
